# GUI ↔ MCP parity

Budgie exposes the same user-facing capabilities through the **HTML GUI** and **MCP tools**. Both must stay in sync.

## Manifest

[`src/capabilities.js`](src/capabilities.js) is the single source of truth. Every capability has:

- `id` — stable identifier
- `kind` — `"read"` or `"write"`
- `gui` — `{ method, path }` matching the route in `index.js`
- `mcpTool` — tool name in `src/mcp/tools.js`
- `skipTick` (optional) — only `list_transactions` skips schedule tick

## Adding a feature

When adding any user-facing action:

1. Add an entry to `src/capabilities.js`
2. Add mutation logic to `src/actions.js` (writes)
3. Add HTTP route in `src/index.js` (GUI)
4. Add MCP tool definition + handler in `src/mcp/tools.js`
5. Run `bun test test/mcp-parity.test.js`

## Rules

- **No GUI-only mutations** — every `POST` route must have a matching MCP write tool
- **No MCP-only mutations** — do not expose service functions via MCP unless the GUI also exposes them
- **Shared write path** — HTTP POST handlers call `actions.*`; MCP tools call the same functions
- **Money at boundary** — `dollarsToCents()` in HTTP/MCP layers only; services use integer cents
- **Cadence** — use `parseCadenceFields()` (HTTP) or equivalent JSON args (MCP)
- **Schedule tick** — `maybeTick()` on HTTP page loads (skip `/ledger/rows`); MCP calls `maybeTick()` before every tool except `list_transactions`
- **Bank transactions** — enter only via OFX/QFX import (GUI upload or `import_ofx` tool)

## Excluded (internal only)

Do not expose via GUI or MCP:

- Manual transaction entry (`addIncome` / `addExpense` except via import/schedules)
- Schedule `update*` functions (create/toggle/delete only in GUI)
- Direct `transferAccounts` (import and transfer linking handle this)

## Transport

Two MCP transports share the same tools and dispatch logic (`src/mcp/dispatch.js`):

| Transport | Entry | When to use |
|-----------|-------|-------------|
| **stdio** | `bun run src/mcp.js` | Cursor default; no web server required |
| **Streamable HTTP** | `POST /mcp` on the Bun web server | Remote clients or when Budgie is already running |

No auth — same trust model as the web app (localhost/LAN). This is **not** a public REST JSON API.
